Libraries

library(ggplot2)

Abstract

In this short analysis, I will be looking at some sample vehicle data with the goal of finding anything useful.

Data Wrangle

Lets take a look at which dealers input the most vehicles. Hopefully, we can gain some insight about which vehicles are most prominent.

dealer_vehicle <- vehicle_data |>
  select(c(vin, dealer_name, dealer_id, dealer_contact_province, country)) |> 
  group_by(dealer_id) |> 
  summarise(dealer_count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(dealer_count))

head(dealer_vehicle)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   dealer_id dealer_count
##   <fct>            <int>
## 1 153              38777
## 2 10380            12344
## 3 23                7610
## 4 4562              7115
## 5 28620             5617
## 6 22292             5443

This shows us how often each dealer is searching for a vehicle. We can gain insight about which dealers use the product the most often.

Getting somewhere

Group by vin and dealer. Province added in but can’t be grouped.

vin1 <- vehicle_data |> 
  group_by(vin, dealer_id, dealer_contact_province) |> 
  summarise(count = n())

head(vin1)
## # A tibble: 6 × 4
## # Groups:   vin, dealer_id [6]
##   vin               dealer_id dealer_contact_province count

## 5 137ZA9038YE186519 8172      ON                          1

It is apparent that some specific vins are being input to the tool at various locations. Furthermore, we can dig into specifics of the vin to find out which types of vehicles are being put into the tool most often. Let’s quickly group by vin to see which vins show up more than once. This will tell us which vehicles are being looked at in various locations.

vin_grouped <- vin1 |> 
  group_by(vin) |> 
  summarise(vin_count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(vin_count))

head(vin_grouped)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   vin               vin_count

## 4 WBA13AW07PFN64922         8
## 5 1GYFZER41KF157680         7
## 6 3CZRU6H31KG726763         7

There are some high traffic vins. 13 dealers have looked at the top vin.

Top Vins

Wrangling the data from the grouped vins, we can gather the first 8 digits of the vin too see which vehicles are showing up the most often in the data.

vin2 <- vin_grouped |> 
  mutate(
    car = substr(vin, 1, 8)
    ) |> 
  select(-vin_count, -vin)|> 
  group_by(car) |> 
  summarise(count_similar = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(count_similar))

head(vin2)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   car      count_similar
##   <chr>            <int>
## 1 5YJ3E1EA          1235
## 2 1FTEW1EP           653
## 3 1C4RJFBG           645
## 4 1N4AL3AP           616
## 5 5YJ3E1EB           600
## 6 1FT7W2BT           578

Lets plot this to see the top 25 vehicles.

plot0 <- vin2 |> 
  slice_head(n = 25) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(car, -count_similar),
             y = count_similar,
             fill = count_similar)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = 'orange', high = 'red') +
  labs(x = 'Car', y = 'Count', title = 'Top 25 Cars') + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

plot0

Great! Now it is apparent which type of vehicles are most commonly searched. The top vin relates to a tesla.

Lets do the same but for more specific details

Top 100 vehicle make (vin 1-3)

looking it at like this, we see that there are far more occurrences of 1FT which relates too a ford truck.

vin3 <- vin_grouped |> 
  mutate(
    make = substr(vin, 1,3),
    ) |> 
  select(-vin_count) |> 
  group_by(make) |> 
  summarise(make_count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(make_count))

head(vin3)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   make  make_count
##   <chr>      <int>
## 1 1FT         8425
## 2 1C4         8323
## 3 1FM         6281
## 4 1G1         4691
## 5 1C6         4026
## 6 1GC         3809
make_frame <- vin3 |> 
  slice_head(n = 100) |> 
  mutate(category = case_when(
    row_number() <= 25 ~ 'Top 25 Vehicles By Make',
    (row_number() > 25 & row_number() <= 50) ~ '26 - 50 Vehicles By Make',
    (row_number() > 50 & row_number() <= 75) ~ '51 - 75 Vehicles By Make',
    row_number() > 75 ~ 'Last 25 Vehicles By Make'
  ))
plot1 <- make_frame[1:25,] |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(make, -make_count),
             y = make_count,
             fill = make_count)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = 'lightblue', high = 'darkblue') +
  labs(x = 'Make', y = 'Count', title = 'Top 25 Vehicle Makes') + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))


plot2 <- make_frame[26:50,] |>

By description section

descr_frame <- vin_grouped |> 
  mutate(
    descr = substr(vin, 4,8)
    ) |> 
  select(-vin_count) |> 
  group_by(descr) |> 
  summarise(descr_count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(descr_count)) |> 
  slice_head(n = 100) |> 
  mutate(category = case_when(
    row_number() <= 25 ~ 'Top 25 Vehicles By descr',
    (row_number() > 25 & row_number() <= 50) ~ '26 - 50 Vehicles By descr',
    (row_number() > 50 & row_number() <= 75) ~ '51 - 75 Vehicles By descr',
    row_number() > 75 ~ 'Last 25 Vehicles By descr'
  ))

By year

year_frame <- vin_grouped |> 
  mutate(year = substr(vin, 10, 10)) |> 
  select(-vin_count) |> 
  group_by(year) |> 
  summarise(year_count = n()) |> 
  arrange(desc(year_count)) |> 
  slice_head(n = 100)

dim(year_frame)
## [1] 45  2

There are 45 total year counts from from sept. 1 - sept. 18. There is no need to random sample from the dataset, when grouped by year. A visual of top years follows.

plot5 <- year_frame |>
